{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778701011,"nonce":"c6JaZFdQGMKWHJufacAWMFBiQS4=","message":"## Additional motivation: post-go-lag interpretation\n\nThis session's investigation surfaced that the post-go velocity lag (~3–5 timesteps before acceleration ramps up) is **filter-bound, not damping-induced** — at v=0 the damping force is zero, so the lag is set by the first-order force-filter step response (~63% of target force by step 5 at τ=50 ms). Full analytic table in \\`c99ad9d\\` comment same session.\n\n**Implication for this sweep:** if the goal is to test the filter-bound-lag hypothesis directly, a τ-filter mini-sweep (τ ∈ {50, 25, 10} ms at fixed k = 10) would be a more pointed diagnostic than a k-sweep alone — the lag should scale linearly with τ while remaining approximately invariant to k for v near zero. The k-sweep this issue proposes still has independent value (parameter-regime vs objective-form decoupling per the original framing), but a τ-sweep is the more direct test of the specific velocity-onset signature.\n\n**New decision records cross-ref:**\n- \\`a04711e\\` — choice of k=10 (biomechanical defensibility audit).\n- \\`08c49e3\\` — choice of τ=50 ms (literature consistency check).\n- \\`c99ad9d\\` — full post-go-lag framing comment.","files":null}]}